 that ofthe immensely more important, bitter, and modest Audace. Gerry was a bigflabby hulk of a man who must have been nearing sixty when after a life ofaesthetic asceticism he surprised his special coterie by marrying thatporcelain-pretty and very fast girl. His famous essays--on Donne, on Villon,on Eliot--his philosophic poetry, his recent Laic Litanies and so forthmeant nothing to me, but he was an appealing old drunk, whose humor anderudition could break the resistance of the most unsociabl